column12: PATIENT INTERFACE
column13: A cushion module for a patient interface is disclosed. The cushion module comprising a first cavity, a second cavity, a nasal aperture and an oral aperture. The first and second cavities are separated by a cavity wall that enables respiratory gas to flow within the cushion module between the first and second cavities when in use. Additionally, the first cavity is configured to communicate respiratory gas to both the mouth and the nares of a patient via the oral aperture and the nasal aperture respectively. The cushion module comprises an exhaust vent to communicate respiratory gas from within the cushion module to externally of the cushion module and the second cavity is in communication with the exhaust vent. Also disclosed are a cavity wall and a cushion module.

column12: Loss mitigation implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an insured asset and the area surrounding an insured asset, such as with the policyholder or insured's permission and collect data related to the insured asset, such as images, video, audio, weather conditions, thermal signatures, wood and soil samples, etc., and transmit this data to a computing device. The computing device may be associated with and/or utilized by an insurance provider to perform insurance-related tasks, such as processing the data to determine an amount of risk associated with the insured asset. If the amount of risk has increased, the computing device may provide a recommendation to a mobile device of the policyholder on how to reduce the risk such that corrective action may be taken. Insurance discounts may be provided based upon following recommendations that mitigate risk.

column12: Accident reconstruction implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate the generation of a virtual reconstruction model of a vehicle collision. UAVs may collect data (including images) related to the vehicle collision, such as with the insured's permission, which may be received by an external computing device associated with the insurer and utilized to perform a photogrammetric analysis of the images to determine vehicle impact points, the road layout at the scene of the collision, the state of the traffic light at the scene of the collision, the speeds and directions of vehicles, etc. This data may be used to generate a virtual reconstruction model of the vehicle collision. An insurer may use the virtual reconstruction model to perform various insurance-related tasks, such as allocating fault to drivers or autonomous vehicles involved in the vehicle collision, and adjustment of insurance pricing based upon the fault allocation.

column12: Accident fault determination implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively survey an area or be dispatched to the scene of a vehicle collision or crash, such as with an insured's permission, and collect data related to the vehicle collision or crash, such as vehicle data, insurer data, images, video, audio, weather conditions, etc., and transmit this data to a computing device. The computing device may be associated with an insurer and/or utilized by an insurer to perform insurance-related tasks, such as processing the data to assign fault to one or more parties or vehicles, such as autonomous vehicles, involved in the vehicle collision or crash, using the fault assignment to open or otherwise process an insurance claim, modifying a premium price, updating qualified discounts, etc. The drone data may also assist an insurer in opening an insurance claim by prepopulating fields associated with a submitted claim form.

column12: Patient interface
column13: A cushion module for a patient interface is disclosed. The cushion module comprising a first cavity, a second cavity, a nasal aperture and an oral aperture. The first and second cavities are separated by a cavity wall that enables respiratory gas to flow within the cushion module between the first and second cavities when in use. Additionally, the first cavity is configured to communicate respiratory gas to both the mouth and the nares of a patient via the oral aperture and the nasal aperture respectively. The cushion module comprises an exhaust vent to communicate respiratory gas from within the cushion module to externally of the cushion module and the second cavity is in communication with the exhaust vent. Also disclosed are a cavity wall and a cushion module.

column12: INSURANCE UNDERWRITING AND RE-UNDERWRITING IMPLEMENTING UNMANNED AERIAL VEHICLES (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an area surrounding a property, and collect data related to property. A location for an inspection of a property to be conducted by a UAV may be received, and one or more images depicting a view of the location may be displayed via a user interface. Additionally, a geofence boundary may be determined based on an area corresponding to a property boundary, where the geofence boundary represents a geospatial boundary in which to limit flight of the UAV. Furthermore, a navigation route may be determined which corresponds to the geofence boundary for inspection of the property by the UAV, the navigation route having waypoints, each waypoint indicating a location for the UAV to obtain drone data. The UAV may be directed around the property using the determined navigation route.

column12: Loss mitigation implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an insured asset and the area surrounding an insured asset, such as with the policyholder or insured's permission and collect data related to the insured asset, such as images, video, audio, weather conditions, thermal signatures, wood and soil samples, etc., and transmit this data to a computing device. The computing device may be associated with and/or utilized by an insurance provider to perform insurance-related tasks, such as processing the data to determine an amount of risk associated with the insured asset. If the amount of risk has increased, the computing device may provide a recommendation to a mobile device of the policyholder on how to reduce the risk such that corrective action may be taken. Insurance discounts may be provided based upon following recommendations that mitigate risk.

column12: ACUTE HEALTH EVENT MONITORING
column13: A system comprises processing circuitry and memory comprising program instructions that, when executed by the processing circuitry, cause the processing circuitry to: apply a first set of rules to first patient parameter data for a first determination of whether sudden cardiac arrest of a patient is detected; determine that a one or more context criteria of the first determination are satisfied; and in response to satisfaction of the context criteria, apply a second set of rules to second patient parameter data for a second determination of whether sudden cardiac arrest of the patient is detected. At least the second set of rules comprises a machine learning model, and the second patient parameter data comprises at least one patient parameter that is not included in the first patient parameter data.

column12: Insurance underwriting and re-underwriting implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an area surrounding an insured or potentially insured asset, such as with the insurance customer's permission, and collect data related to the insured or potentially insured asset, such as size, height, roof shape, materials (siding, roofing), etc. which may form a basis of the underwriting detail used to evaluate a property. column12: AUTOMATIC ALERT CONTROL FOR ACUTE HEALTH EVENT
column13: An example device of a patient includes an antenna configured to wirelessly receive communication from a medical device; and processing circuitry coupled to the antenna and configured to: determine that the received communication indicates that a patient is experiencing an acute health event; in response to the determination, determine one or more physical states of the patient based on sensed data from one or more sensors; confirm that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event based on the determined one or more physical states; and output information based on the confirmation that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event.

column12: Unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) data collection and claim pre-generation for insured approval
column13: Systems and methods are described for using data collected by unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to generate insurance claim estimates that an insured individual may quickly review, approve, or modify. When an insurance-related event occurs, such as a vehicle collision, crash, or disaster, one or more UAVs are dispatched to the scene of the event to collect various data, including data related to vehicle or real property (insured asset) damage. With the insured's permission or consent, the data collected by the UAVs may then be analyzed to generate an estimated insurance claim for the insured. The estimated insurance claim may be sent to the insured individual, such as to their mobile device via wireless communication or data transmission, for subsequent review and approval. As a result, insurance claim handling and/or the online customer experience may be enhanced.

column12: ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTION IMPLEMENTING UNMANNED AERIAL VEHICLES (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate the generation of a virtual reconstruction model of a vehicle collision. UAVs may collect data (including images) related to the vehicle collision, such as with the insured's permission, which may be received by an external computing device associated with the insurer and utilized to perform a photogrammetric analysis of the images to determine vehicle impact points, the road layout at the scene of the collision, the state of the traffic light at the scene of the collision, the speeds and directions of vehicles, etc. This data may be used to generate a virtual reconstruction model of the vehicle collision. An insurer may use the virtual reconstruction model to perform various insurance-related tasks, such as allocating fault to drivers or autonomous vehicles involved in the vehicle collision, and adjustment of insurance pricing based upon the fault allocation.

column12: DISASTER DAMAGE ANALYSIS AND LOSS MITIGATION IMPLEMENTING UNMANNED AERIAL VEHICLES (UAVS)
column13: Various techniques are described utilizing one or more unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs, or “drones”) for various disaster and/or catastrophe-related purposes. UAVs may collect data in an attempt to predict the occurrence and/or extent of a catastrophe and/or to mitigate the impact of a catastrophe before and, if not at that time, once it has occurred. The UAVs may perform various tasks such that the damage to property caused by a catastrophe (or potential catastrophe) may be eliminated or mitigated. The drone data may be transmitted by the UAVs to an external computing device, which may be associated with an insurer and used, with an insured's permission, to begin and/or facilitate an insurance claim process or other various insurance-related tasks. Damage to insured property may be estimated from the drone data, and proposed or estimated insurance claims may be generated for customer review, modification, or approval.

column12: INSURANCE UNDERWRITING AND RE-UNDERWRITING IMPLEMENTING UNMANNED AERIAL VEHICLES (UAVS)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an area surrounding a property, and collect data related to property. A location for an inspection of a property to be conducted by a UAV may be received, and one or more images depicting a view of the location may be displayed via a user interface. Additionally, a geofence boundary may be determined based on an area corresponding to a property boundary, where the geofence boundary represents a geospatial boundary in which to limit flight of the UAV. Furthermore, a navigation route may be determined which corresponds to the geofence boundary for inspection of the property by the UAV, the navigation route having waypoints, each waypoint indicating a location for the UAV to obtain drone data. The UAV may be directed around the property using the determined navigation route.

column12: PATIENT INTERFACE
column13: A cushion module for a patient interface is disclosed. The cushion module comprising a first cavity, a second cavity, a nasal aperture and an oral aperture. The first and second cavities are separated by a cavity wall that enables respiratory gas to flow within the cushion module between the first and second cavities when in use. Additionally, the first cavity is configured to communicate respiratory gas to both the mouth and the nares of a patient via the oral aperture and the nasal aperture respectively. The cushion module comprises an exhaust vent to communicate respiratory gas from within the cushion module to externally of the cushion module and the second cavity is in communication with the exhaust vent. Also disclosed are a cavity wall and a cushion module.

column12: Patient interface
column13: A cushion module for a patient mask comprises an interior volume divided into two cavities 1032, 1030 by a separating cavity wall 1050. An inspiratory conduit 1342 is configured to deliver respiratory gas to the first cavity 1032 a primary flow cavity. An expiratory conduit 1320 is configured to receive respiratory gas from the second cavity 1030. The first cavity can be a primary flow cavity 1032 and the second cavity can be an exhaust flow cavity 1030. The inspiratory conduit 1342 and the expiratory conduit 1320 can be co-axial. The expiratory conduit 1320 can surround the inspiratory conduit 1342. The conduits can diverge at a distance from the mask’s frame (fig 80). The first conduit 1520 and the second conduit 1530 can be spaced apart at the cushion module. The conduits can be connected to permit limited rotational movement of one or both conduits.

column12: AUTOMATIC ALERT CONTROL FOR ACUTE HEALTH EVENT
column13: An example device of a patient includes an antenna configured to wirelessly receive communication from a medical device; and processing circuitry coupled to the antenna and configured to: determine that the received communication indicates that a patient is experiencing an acute health event; in response to the determination, determine one or more physical states of the patient based on sensed data from one or more sensors; confirm that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event based on the determined one or more physical states; and output information based on the confirmation that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event.

column12: Systems and methods of utilizing unmanned vehicles to detect insurance claim buildup
column13: The present embodiments relate to detecting fraudulent insurance claims. According to certain aspects, a central monitoring server may receive and examine data detected by at least one unmanned vehicle and generate an estimated insurance claim for a loss event. The central monitoring server may then receive an actual insurance claim relating to the loss event, and may compare the estimated insurance claim to the actual insurance claim to identify potential buildup included in the actual insurance claim. If buildup is detected, the central monitoring server may then process the actual insurance claim accordingly based upon the potential buildup. As a result, claim monies may be paid to insureds that more accurately reflect actual losses resulting from the loss event, and insurance cost savings may be ultimately passed onto typical insurance customers.

column12: Insurance underwriting and re-underwriting implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an area surrounding an insured or potentially insured asset, such as with the insurance customer's permission, and collect data related to the insured or potentially insured asset, such as size, height, roof shape, materials (siding, roofing), etc. which may form a basis of the underwriting detail used to evaluate a property. The drone data may reveal site characteristics, such as slope or grade of a parcel; the proximity to other structures (and their uses); trees; rivers; coastlines; and earthquake faults. The drone data may be used by an insurance provider remote server to assess the risk associated with an insured asset, generate or modify an insurance premium or discount, etc. The drone data may also be used to mitigate risk and prevent loss by alerting policyholders of the risk such that corrective action may be taken.

column12: Loss mitigation implementing unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)
column13: Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) may facilitate insurance-related tasks. UAVs may actively be dispatched to an insured asset and the area surrounding an insured asset, such as with the policyholder or insured's permission and collect data related to the insured asset, such as images, video, audio, weather conditions, thermal signatures, wood and soil samples, etc., and transmit this data to a computing device. The computing device may be associated with and/or utilized by an insurance provider to perform insurance-related tasks, such as processing the data to determine an amount of risk associated with the insured asset. If the amount of risk has increased, the computing device may provide a recommendation to a mobile device of the policyholder on how to reduce the risk such that corrective action may be taken. Insurance discounts may be provided based upon following recommendations that mitigate risk.

column12: Automatic alert control for acute health event
column13: An example device of a patient includes an antenna configured to wirelessly receive communication from a medical device; and processing circuitry coupled to the antenna and configured to: determine that the received communication indicates that a patient is experiencing an acute health event; in response to the determination, determine one or more physical states of the patient based on sensed data from one or more sensors; confirm that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event based on the determined one or more physical states; and output information based on the confirmation that the patient is not experiencing the acute health event.

column12: Patient interface
column13: A cushion module for a patient interface is disclosed. The cushion module includes a first cavity, a second cavity, a nostril orifice, and an oral orifice. The first cavity and the second cavity are separated by a cavity wall that, when in use, enables breathing gas to flow between the first cavity and the second cavity within the cushion module. Additionally, the first lumen is configured to deliver breathing gas to both the mouth and the nostrils of the patient via the oral orifice and the nostril orifice, respectively. The cushion module includes a vent hole to deliver breathing gas from within the cushion module to an exterior of the cushion module, and the second cavity is in communication with the vent hole. A cavity wall and a cushion module are also disclosed.

column12: Percutaneous perforation closure systems, devices, and methods
column13: A device for sealing an aperture in a tissue includes: an implant configured to seal the aperture when positioned adjacent to the aperture; and a delivery shaft configured to engage the implant to allow the implant to be maneuvered into sealing engagement with a distal surface of the tissue, the delivery shaft comprising a retaining sleeve comprising a locking projection engagable with the locking recess of the implant to secure the implant to the delivery shaft, and a release sleeve axially slideable relative to the retaining sleeve between a first axial position in which the release sleeve is configured to maintain locking engagement between the locking recess and the locking projection, and a second axial position in which the release sleeve permits the locking projection to disengage the locking recess.

column12: GROUP COORDINATION OF OPERATIONAL FEATURES OF A PLURALITY OF MEDICAL DEVICES
column13: Embodiments include a system providing group coordination of operational features of a plurality of medical devices. The system includes a plurality of medical devices each including a control engine having a set of device-specific parameters governing operation of an operational feature. The system also includes a rack providing a mounting structure for coupling the plurality of medical devices by releasable engagement. The system further includes a communication architecture in the rack providing connectivity between the plurality of medical devices when the plurality of medical devices are coupled to the rack. The control engines in the plurality of medical devices are interoperable with respect to the operational feature and automatically modify the set of device-specific parameters in each one of the plurality of medical devices when coupled to the rack for group coordination of the operational feature.

column12: FAHRZEUGE MIT STEUERSYSTEMEN ZUM AUSFÜHREN VERSCHIEDENER FUNKTIONEN BASIEREND AUF NUTZLASTGEWICHT UND VERFAHREN ZUM BETREIBEN DIESER
column13: Hierin offenbart sind Fahrzeuge und Verfahren zum Betreiben von Fahrzeugen. Ein Fahrzeug beinhaltet einen Hauptrahmen, ein Arbeitsanbaugerät und ein Steuersystem. Das Arbeitsanbaugerät wird von dem Hauptrahmen getragen und ist konfiguriert, um eine Nutzlast bei Verwendung des Fahrzeugs zu tragen. Das Steuersystem wird von dem Hauptrahmen getragen und ist konfiguriert, um den Betrieb des Fahrzeugs zu steuern. Das Steuersystem beinhaltet ein Nutzlastmesssystem, das konfiguriert ist, um eine Nutzlasteingabe bereitzustellen, die eine variable Nutzlast angibt, die von dem Arbeitsanbaugerät bei Verwendung des Fahrzeugs getragen wird, und eine Steuerung, die mit dem Nutzlastmesssystem gekoppelt ist.

column12: veículo, e, método para operar um veículo
column13: veículo, e, método para operar um veículo. veículos e métodos para operar veículos são descritos aqui. um veículo inclui uma armação principal, um implemento de trabalho, e um sistema de controle. o implemento de trabalho é suportado pela armação principal e configurado para transportar uma carga útil no uso do veículo. o sistema de controle é suportado pela armação principal e configurado para controlar a operação do veículo. o sistema de controle inclui um sistema de medição de carga útil configurado para prover entrada de carga útil indicativa de uma carga útil variável suportada pelo implemento de trabalho no uso do veículo e um controlador acoplado ao sistema de medição de carga útil.

column12: Instrumento para analizar muestras biológicas y reactivos
column13: Un instrumento (100) para procesar una muestra biológica, comprendiendo el instrumento: un conjunto de trayectoria de cintas (118), configurado para hacer avanzar una cinta (104) con una matriz de pocillos a lo largo de una trayectoria de cintas a través del instrumento (100); un conjunto de dispensación (114), configurado para aspirar y dispensar la muestra biológica y un reactivo en la matriz de pocillos de la cinta (104) para formar una mezcla de muestra biológica y reactivo; un conjunto de sellado (120), configurado para sellar la mezcla de muestra biológica y reactivo de la cinta (104) con un sello (106); y un conjunto de amplificación y detección (122), configurado para detectar una señal de la mezcla de muestra biológica y reactivo en la matriz de pocillos de la cinta (104), en donde el conjunto de amplificación y detección (122) incluye una unidad térmica (210) situada en la trayectoria de cintas, configurada para controlar la temperatura de la mezcla de muestra biológica y reactivo en la matriz de pocillos de la cinta (104), estando el instrumento (100) caracterizado por que la unidad térmica (210) comprende una pluralidad de cavidades (1022) configuradas para recibir los respectivos pocillos de la matriz de pocillos, siendo las cavidades (1022) ligeramente más pequeñas o del mismo tamaño que los pocillos de la cinta (104), para así formar un contacto estable entre la superficie interior de las cavidades (1022) de la unidad térmica (210) y la superficie exterior de los pocillos de la cinta (104) cuando la cinta (104) esté situada en un lado superior de la unidad térmica (210); y por que el instrumento (100) comprende, además una cámara de presión calentada (212) situada por encima de la unidad térmica (210) y la cinta (104), configurada para presurizar el espacio por encima del sello (106) de la cinta (104) para crear una fuerza que empuje contra el sello (106) cuando la cinta (104) esté situada en un lado superior de la unidad térmica (210).

column12: PRINT JOB DISTRIBUTION ACROSS A NETWORK OF 3D PRINTERS
column13: Disclosed herein is a technique to efficiently distribute a large number of printable CAD objects to a group of printers having variable settings and/or parameters. Each CAD object includes metadata specifying a particular set of production parameters (e.g., software settings, post-processing steps, production material, and/or physical location). The technique positions objects with the same set of production parameters metadata in similar print cycles subject to object nesting optimization.

column12: SUBSTITUTED N-PHENYL SULFONAMIDE BRADYKININ ANTAGONISTS
column13: Disclosed are certain substituted N-phenylsulfonamide derivatives and related compounds. These compounds are useful as bradykinin antagonists to relieve adverse symptoms in mammals mediated, at least in part, by bradykinin including pain, inflammation, bronchoconstriction, cerebral edema, etc.

column12: PRINT JOB DISTRIBUTION ACROSS A NETWORK OF 3D PRINTERS
column13: Disclosed herein is a technique to efficiently distribute a large number of printable CAD objects to a group of printers having variable settings and/or parameters. Each CAD object includes metadata specifying a particular set of production parameters (e.g., software settings, post-processing steps, production material, and/or physical location). The technique positions objects with the same set of production parameters metadata in similar print cycles subject to object nesting optimization.

column12: FLOWSPEC MESSAGE PROCESSING APPARATUS AND METHOD
column13: A method and apparatus for processing flow specification (Flowspec) messages to one or more of a plurality of customer networks by a controller device coupled to the plurality of customer networks. Preferably a network controller monitors network traffic flowing through each of the customer networks for detecting a network attack in one of the plurality of customer networks, via monitoring of the network traffic. Upon detection of a network attack, a Flowspec message is generated for the customer network detected to be under network attack wherein the Flowspec message is configured specifically for that customer network. The generated Flowspec message is transmitted to the customer network detected to be under network attack for implementation by the customer network for mitigation of the detected network attack.

column12: INSTRUMENT FOR ANALYZING BIOLOGICAL SAMPLES AND REAGENTS
column13: An instrument for processing a biological sample includes a chassis. Connected to the chassis is a tape path along which a tape with a matrix of wells can be automatically advanced through the instrument, a dispensing assembly for dispensing the biological sample and a reagent into the matrix of wells of the tape to form a biological sample and reagent mixture, a sealing assembly for sealing the biological sample and reagent mixture in the tape, and an amplification and detection assembly for detecting a signal from the biological sample and reagent mixture in the matrix of wells in the tape.

column12: BIOLOGICAL SAMPLES AND REAGENTS ANALYSIS DEVICE
column13: FIELD: physics.SUBSTANCE: biological sample processing device comprises chassis. Tape is connected to chassis along which tape with matrix of holes can automatically move through device, dosing unit for dispensing biological sample and reagent into matrix of holes on tape to form mixture of biological sample and reagent, a sealing assembly for sealing a biological sample and a reagent in a tape and an amplification and detection unit for detecting a signal from a mixture of a biological sample and a reagent in the matrix of the wells in the tape. Amplification and detection system comprises a thermal module located on a tape path, configuration and arrangement of which enable it to adjust the temperature of the mixture of the biological sample and reagent in the matrix of the wells on the tape. Thermal module comprises multiple cavities capable of receiving wells from matrix of wells, wherein each cavity has such size to form tight contact between outer surface of the hole and inner surface of the cavity.EFFECT: technical result is an increase in the functionality of the device.16 cl, 53 dwg

column12: ACUTE HEALTH EVENT MONITORING
column13: A system comprises processing circuitry and memory comprising program instructions that, when executed by the processing circuitry, cause the processing circuitry to: apply a first set of rules to first patient parameter data for a first determination of whether sudden cardiac arrest of a patient is detected; determine that a one or more context criteria of the first determination are satisfied; and m response to satisfaction of the context criteria, apply a second set of rides to second patient parameter data for a second determination of whether sudden cardiac arrest of the patient is detected. At least the second set of rules comprises a machine learning model, and the second patient parameter data comprises at least one patient parameter that is not included m the first patient parameter data.

column12: METHOD FOR PROGRAMMING AN INFUSION PUMP AND METHOD FOR PROGRAMMING AN INJECTION PUMP
column13: A method for programming an infusion pump and a method for programming an injection pump are provided, the method comprising: providing an infusion pump comprising a processor, a memory operably coupled to the processor, an infusion pump touch screen interface, and a haptic infusion pump interface, the processor is configured to display infusion pump data using the infusion pump touch screen interface and receive infusion pump data from the infusion pump touch screen interface and the haptic infusion pump interface; receiving at least one infusion pump programming input on the infusion pump touch screen interface; receiving an infusion pump start command on the tactile infusion pump interface; and in response to an infusion pump starting command, locking an infusion pump touch screen interface when infusion is started.

column12: Load-based adjustment system of implement control parameters and method of use
column13: A work machine includes a chassis, a boom coupled to the chassis, and a work implement coupled to the boom and movable relative to the chassis. In system may further include dynamic payload weighing system configured to measure the payload weight on the work implement. The system may also include an electrohydraulic system controller in communication with the dynamic payload weighing system and an electrohydraulic control valve electrically coupled to the electrohydraulic system controller and moveable to a plurality of weight-specific valve positions based on the measured payload weight on the implement.

column12: LASTBASIERTES ANPASSUNGSSYSTEM FÜR STEUERPARAMETER VON ANBAUGERÄTEN UND VERFAHREN ZU DEREN VERWENDUNG
column13: Eine Arbeitsmaschine beinhaltet ein Fahrgestell, ein Ausleger, der mit dem Fahrgestell gekoppelt ist, und ein Arbeitsanbaugerät, das mit dem Ausleger gekoppelt und relativ zum Fahrgestell beweglich ist. Im System kann ferner ein dynamisches Nutzlastwägesystem enthalten sein, das so konfiguriert ist, dass es das Nutzlastgewicht auf dem Arbeitsanbaugerät misst. Das System kann auch eine elektrohydraulische Systemsteuerung enthalten, die mit dem dynamischen Nutzlastwägesystem in Verbindung steht, sowie ein elektrohydraulisches Steuerventil, das elektrisch mit der elektrohydraulischen Systemsteuerung gekoppelt ist und abhängig vom gemessenen Nutzlastgewicht auf dem Anbaugerät in eine Vielzahl von gewichtsabhängigen Ventilstellungen bewegt werden kann.

column12: DEVICE LINKING
column13: Device linking is described. In one or more implementations, data is maintained at a network service that describes characteristics of a plurality of devices that are associated with a user account of the network service. A communication is formed to be received by one of the plurality of devices that includes a portion of the data that pertains to another one of the plurality of devices and that is suitable by the receiving device to discover the other one of the plurality of devices to initiate a local network connection between the devices.

column12: ACUTE HEALTH EVENT MONITORING AND VERIFICATION
column13: Devices, systems, and techniques are disclosed for verifying the occurrence of an acute health event. An example device includes communication circuitry configured to receive a communication indicative of an acute health event of a patient and memory communicatively coupled to the communication circuitry and being configured to store the indication of the acute health event. The device includes processing circuitry communicatively coupled to the communication circuitry and the memory. The processing circuitry is configured to, in response to the communication, verify the acute health event and based on the verification of the acute health event, send an alert regarding the acute health event.

In one or more implementations, data is maintained at a network service that describes characteristics of a plurality of devices that are associated with a user account of the network service. A communication is formed to be received by one of the plurality of devices that includes a portion of the data that pertains to another one of the plurality of devices and that is suitable by the receiving device to discover the other one of the plurality of devices to initiate a local network connection between the devices.

column12: ACUTE HEALTH EVENT MONITORING AND VERIFICATION
column13: Devices, systems, and techniques are disclosed for verifying the occurrence of an acute health event. An example device includes communication circuitry configured to receive a communication indicative of an acute health event of a patient and memory communicatively coupled to the communication circuitry and being configured to store the indication of the acute health event. The device includes processing circuitry communicatively coupled to the communication circuitry and the memory. The processing circuitry is configured to, in response to the communication, verify the acute health event and based on the verification of the acute health event, send an alert regarding the acute health event.

column12: método implementado por um ou mais dispositivos computacionais e dispositivo computacional
column13: resumo patente de invenção: "ligação entre dispositivos". a presente invenção refere-se à ligação entre dispositivos. em uma ou mais implementações, os dados são mantidos em um serviço de rede que descreve características de uma pluralidade de dispositivos que estão associados a uma conta de usuário do serviço de rede. é formada uma comunicação para ser recebida por um da pluralidade de dispositivos que inclui uma porção dos dados que pertencem ao outro da pluralidade de dispositivos e que é apropriado pelo dispositivo de recepção para constatar o outro da pluralidade de dispositivos para iniciar uma conexão de rede local entre os dispositivos.
